Found the root causes. There are two issues:

**1. Vercel masks the problem via its CDN**

Vercel automatically serves images in the best format (WebP/AVIF) based on the browser's `Accept` header, regardless of what file format is stored. Linux/nginx serves files exactly as stored — so only pre-generated WebP files from `next-image-export-optimizer` will be served as WebP.

**2. Content images fall back to plain `<img>` when dimensions are unknown**

In `MarkdownRenderer.tsx:139-153`, `ExportedImage` (which triggers WebP generation) is only used when `width && height` are both set. If `rehype-image-metadata` can't read dimensions (SVG without viewBox, file not found, etc.), the code falls through to a plain `<img>` tag at line 153 — `next-image-export-optimizer` never processes those images.

```typescript
// line 139 — only this path generates WebP
if (width && height) {
  return <ExportedImage ... unoptimized={isDev || isExternal} />;
}
// line 153 — plain img, never WebP-optimized
return <img src={imageSrc} alt={alt || ''} ... />;
```

**Fix**: Use `ExportedImage` for all local images, even without known dimensions. When dimensions are unavailable, pass reasonable defaults and override sizing via CSS:

